[3] Geosentinel, screening of returning Hajj pilgrims
Date: 6 Nov 2013
From: Prof. Philippe Parola, MD, PhD,
<pparola@geosentinel.org>


The Hajj is the largest annual mass gathering in the world with nearly [2-Â­3] million Muslims from more than 180 countries making the pilgrimage to the holy places of Islam in the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia (KSA). The risk of spread of illnesses via the respiratory route has been previously documented and the risk of virus transmission is of concern (1, 2).

In October 2013, multiple surveillance sites within GeoSentinel, the global surveillance network of the International Society of Travel Medicine (ISTM), have reported ill returnees from the Hajj with respiratory illness. Several have been hospitalized and screened for corona virus (MERS) and other pathogens, including influenza.

Although none of these patients has been found to have been infected with MERS, 7 cases of A influenza (those that have been subtyped have been H3N2) have been identified in these returning Hajj travelers. Three have been identified in France, with 4 from Marseille (among the 1st 10 ill returnees tested) and 1 from Saint-Mande (communicated by Prof. Christophe Rapp) sites, respectively.

Ontario, Canada, has also documented significant influenza activity among Hajj attendees. Public Health Ontario Laboratories have tested 26 patients for MERS-CoV in the month of October, and detected 7 cases of influenza. These include: 5 influenza A(H3N2), 1 influenza A (H1N1) pdm09, in persons who had returned from The Hajj, and 1 A (H1N1)pdm09 in a child of travelers to the Hajj.

Finally, the preliminary results of the systematic detection of respiratory virus among a cohort of 130 pilgrims departed from Marseille, France, and just returned from Mecca, have shown that about 8 percent of them carry influenza viruses (mostly A H3N2, 1 H1N1, and 1 influenza B).

As of [30 Oct 2013] influenza activity remains low in the North American and the European regions (3, 4), however infected returned pilgrims may aid in the early spread of influenza this season in the northern hemisphere.

Influenza vaccine should be a priority for pilgrims attending the Hajj (5, 6).

References:
1. Benkouiten S, Charrel R, Belhouchat K, Drali T, Salez N, Nougairede A, Zandotti C, Memish ZA, al Masri M, Gaillard C, Parola P, Brouqui P, Gautret P. Circulation of respiratory viruses among pilgrims during the 2012 Hajj pilgrimage. Clin Infect Dis. 2013 Oct;57(7):992-1000<tel:992-1000>. doi: 10.1093/cid/cit446. Epub 2013 Jul 9.<x-apple-data-detectors://5>
2.http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=20604
3.http://www.who.int/influenza/gisrs_laboratory/updates/summaryreport/en/
4.http://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/publications/Publications/131025-SUR-Weekly-Influenza-Surveillance-Overview.pdf
5. Health conditions for travellers to Saudi Arabia for the pilgrimage to Mecca (Hajj). Wkly Epidemiol Rec. 2013 Aug 9;88(32):343-7.24040674<tel:24040674>
6. Prevention of influenza at Hajj: applications for mass gatherings.Haworth E, Barasheed O, Memish ZA, Rashid H, Booy R. J R Soc Med. 2013 Jun;106(6):215-23.

