http://www.geosentinel.org

[ProMED-mail would like to thank Drs. Parola, Gautret and Gubbay for sharing these results with the ProMED community. - Mod.MPP]

[This is the 1st case of MERS-CoV imported into Spain and represents the 151st laboratory confirmed infection with the virus. The investigative reporting presented in the media report by Helen Branswell, together with the results of screening of Hajj pilgrims returning to France and Canada by the Geosentinal network, seem to further support the observation [mostly anecdotal] that the MERS-CoV is at present not easily transmitted, either from the as yet unidentified source animal to humans, or from person-to-person. One wonders how good the compliance to the Saudi recommendation that individuals with immunocompromising states as well as signficant co-morbidities refrain from travel to Saudi Arabia for the Hajj this year (the exact recommendation on the Saudi Hajj website states: "The Saudi Ministry of Health recommends that elderly (above 65 years of age) and those with chronic diseases (e.g. heart disease, kidney disease, respiratory disease, diabetes) and pilgrims with immune deficiency (congenital and acquired), Malignancy and terminal illnesses, pregnant women and children (under 12) coming for Hajj and Umrah this year, to postpone the performance of the Hajj and Umrah for their own safety ." http://www.moh.gov.sa/en/Hajj/Pages/Healthregulations.aspx.) Serious illness has been more frequent in individuals with pre-existing co-morbidities; and milder expressions of infection have been seen in previously healthy individuals, including several cases of asymptomatic infection in known contacts of clinical cases.

The findings of the GeoSentinel network -- the isolation of influenza viruses from individuals with acute respiratory illnesses returning from the Hajj are findings that are consistent with previous findings on attendees of the Hajj in the "pre-MERS-CoV" era. Drs. Parola, Gautret and Gubbay's recommendation that influenza vaccination pre-Hajj would be prudent, as the infected returning Hajj pilgrims might be associated with contributing to the spread of influenza virus upon return. If one checks the Saudi MOH Hajj Health recommendations page states: "The Saudi Ministry of Health recommends that international pilgrims be vaccinated against seasonal influenza before arrival into the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, particularly those at increased risk of severe influenza diseases, including pregnant women, children under 5 years, the elderly, and individuals with underlying health conditions such as HIV/AIDS, asthma, and chronic heart or lung diseases. In Saudi Arabia, seasonal influenza vaccination is recommended for internal pilgrims, particularly those at risk described above, and all health-care workers in the Hajj premises.". (http://www.moh.gov.sa/en/Hajj/Pages/Healthregulations.aspx).

One of the unknowns at present is whether there have been imported cases into countries with limited resources and infrastructure that may be "under the radar" at present. Hopefully, the lack of reported cases is a true negative.

We await further information on results of investigations surrounding possible exposures the imported case in Spain had while in Saudi Arabia.

For the interactive HealthMap/ProMED map of Spain and surrounding countries in Europe, see http://healthmap.org/r/2br3. For the interactive HealthMap/ProMED map of the Middle East region, see http://healthmap.org/r/1HAJ. - Mod.MPP]
